04636nam a22006855i 9780691207193DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912071937 a10.1515/97806912071932doi  a(DE-B1597)544963  a(OCoLC)1143800623  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC571b.M326613 1994eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.5/12/092221 aManent, Pierre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Intellectual History of Liberalism /cPierre Manent. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew French Thought Series ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tCHAPTER I. Europe and the Theologico-Political Problem -- tCHAPTER II. Machiavelli and the Fecundity of Evil -- tCHAPTER III. Hobbes and the New Political Art -- tCHAPTER IV. Locke, Labor, and Property -- tCHAPTER V. Montesquieu and the Separation of Powers -- tCHAPTER VI. Rousseau, Critic of Liberalism -- tCHAPTER VII. Liberalism after the French Revolution -- tCHAPTER VIII. Benjamin Constant and the Liberalism of Opposition -- tCHAPTER IX. François Guizot: The Liberalism of Government -- tCHAPTER X. Tocqueville: Liberalism Confronts Democracy -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHighlighting the social tensions that confront the liberal tradition, Pierre Manent draws a portrait of what we, citizens of modern liberal democracies, have become. For Manent, a discussion of liberalism encompasses the foundations of modern society, its secularism, its individualism, and its conception of rights. The frequent incapacity of the morally neutral, democratic state to further social causes, he argues, derives from the liberal stance that political life does not serve a higher purpose. Through quick-moving, highly synthetic essays, he explores the development of liberal thinking in terms of a single theme: the decline of theological politics. The author traces the liberal stance to Machiavelli, who, in seeking to divorce everyday life from the pervasive influence of the Catholic church, separated politics from all notions of a cosmological order. What followed, as Manent demonstrates in his analyses of Locke, Hobbes, Rousseau, Guizot, and Constant, was the evolving concept of an individual with no goals outside the confines of the self and a state with no purpose but to prevent individuals from dominating one another. Weighing both the positive and negative effects of such a political arrangement, Manent raises important questions about the fundamental political issues of the day, among them the possibility of individual rights being reconciled with the necessary demands of political organization, and the desirability of a government system neutral about religion but not about public morals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberalismxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aBalinski, Rebecca.1 aSeigel, Jerrold E.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691207193zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691207193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691207193.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK